To elaborate, as a 3D artist, the 24G in the Titan is great, and the Quadro is overkill for most studios unless they are doing MASSIVE scenes like Pixar and Dreamworks. From a 3D artist/VFX Artist standpoint, it makes more sense to get 2x Titans because the 24G is plenty for what most 3D artists do, and in Blender you get TWO gpu tiles when rendering which is effectively twice as fast as one Quadro, because Quadros have the same chips as the GeForce cards, while cherry-picked for better performance and stability, two Titans would still outperform a Quadro in most applications, unless you are rendering MASSIVE scenes with image textures that have 4k+ sizes.

Hey Linus, you're not even close to seeing the difference between a professional card and a gamer card : you need a data set.
Put it like this : game editors write heavy games engines for small content and assume loosing fps while professional cards use optimized software on gigantic realtime data streams. Your computer needs to be also optimized for the card : you can't judge a Quadro card in a gamer pc... It requires at a decent Xeon processor and the Micmac that comes with it to shine all it's glory. Note that no Core ixyz extreme can ever compare to a Xeon CPU due to the whole different system architecture. To give you an idea, these are installed on computers designed to run on planes, using plane power at 400hz, guess for what... In this example, the risk here is not loosing fps from 60 (playable) to 44 (still playable) but to loose unique data that you cannot reproduce unless you fly again costing you hundreds of times the whole computer of your dreams ever (talking about microcomputers).
Another point regarding the drivers : these cards will perform at their optimum capabilities on software that was designed for them and require different API rather than the regular DX, OpenGL and so on. So your GeForce will definitely play better on games, but do not compare to a Quadro. I've been using Quadro cards for more than 15 years now and own 4 of them since first Gen. This is really high end hardware, not for gamers.

A fact that isn't being addressed is the fact that these are used sometimes 4 to a 2u enclosure, and with racks on racks of them.  These are used to solve very large problems, and the ecc is quite necessary because if a bit flips on any of them the job could have to be ran over again, so the economics of the extra price of the card make sense.  At a large enough scale these could be a nightmare without ECC.  Think if you were rendering the master cut of avatar, and it took two months to complete, and was corrupted, such that it had to be rerun, pushing back the release date of the film.  Processes that are only as big as one machine (not big data), and that are output immediately to a monitor with little persitence of error, are not really use cases for these cards.

Just to set the record straight: the Quadro RTX 8000 is indeed the most expensive and powerful Turing graphics card in NVIDIA's lineup. The even more powerful and expensive Quadro GV100 and Tesla V100, mentioned in several comments, are Volta-based - the slightly older Volta GPU has more CUDA cores (5120 versus 4608) and twice the tensor cores (640 versus 320) than the fully-fledged TU102 GPU powering the Titan RTX and the Quadro RTX cards, but it nas no RT cores (that was Turing architecture's breakthrough). The Volta architecture also uses faster 4096-bit HBM2 memory with a larger bandwidth, and a twice-as-fast NVLink connection. These two Volta cards (together with their "little" sister, the Titan V) are really more focused on AI, data center and and HPC markets rather than on professional graphics (rendering, 3D modeling, video editing, CAD, etc.), which is the main focus of the Quadro RTX lineup - the Tesla doesn't even have a monitor connection. NVIDIA never released any Volta-based consumer cards - the closest thing to it is the Titan V.

The most important differences between the consumer and professional NVIDIA lineups are the memory (faster, larger and ECC) and the floating-point precision of the GPU. The GeForce RTX lineup (even the 2080 Ti) is severely neutered with respect to the latter, particularly regarding 32-bit (single-precision) floating-point operations. 16-bit (half-precision) and 64-bit (double-precision) floating-point performances of the GeForce RTX 2080 Ti and the Quadro RTX lineup are somewhat closer to each other (about 20% difference in favor to the Quadros). As for the Volta cards, they are sort of matched to Turing in 16-bit floating-point performance, but their 64-bit floating-point performance is vastly superior (more than one order of magnitude) to Turing. Higher performance in floating-point arithmetic is important when the graphics tasks require precision, like in CAD (since CAD models are used as templates for actual manufacturing), which is not so important for gaming graphics, where the focus is rendering speed and eye candy. This difference in focus also explains why most Quadro RTX cards underperform in games (except the top-tier Quadros) but completely obliterate the GeForce RTX lineup in CAD software such as Solidworks or Siemens NX (in AutoCAD, not so much - driver optimization also plays a role here).

When you're designing mission critical things like booster rockets or low-orbit 5G satellites, you've got to have the ECC memory and certifications that guarantee 100% accuracy in the calculations. Could we stop with the "blower style coolers are better suited for cases with less airflow" already, please?
The amount of air of a given temperature you need hitting a given surface for dissipating a given amount of heat is constant, i.e. it does not change, I wish it did but physics...
That is exactly why when you have a smaller dissipating surface area and a smaller fan what you have to do is spin that fan faster just to keep the flow up.
And, ultimately, you still need the same amount of available air for the fan to blow.
And that air has to come from somewhere, so a poorly ventilated case will still be a poorly ventilated case and the card will still run hotter and louder.
But it will probably fit easier, which is what blower style designs are about.

‚Äã@Kacper Sycha ‚Äã Kacper Sycha To me it's actually kind of funny to read things like "only" and "gigabyte" in the same sentence. But that has to do with my first computer experiences being the 8 bit era where you were counting bytes, if not bits trying to stretch the memory as far as possible.

Early processors couldn't even address more than 64KB of memory, and that usually included a system ROM of up to 16KB. This could be worked around using some trickery where you swapped in pages of memory, but it made things harder, and at the time memory was VERY expensive, so you really tried to make do with what you had and use it as efficiently as possible. People came up with all kinds of trick to do this including but not limited to compression and sometimes even self modifying code.

It's really hard to understand how much information can be stored in a GB, and note that when I talk about a GB I'm talking about 1024 bytes times 1024 kilobyte times 1024 megabytes for a total of 1,073,741,824 bytes. That's a number we can understand but not visualize. A kilobyte or 1024 bytes is easy. A megabyte or 1,048,576 bytes is already beyond what we can visualize.
To make it understandable you can take something most of us know or at least has seen and rifled through even if only a minority of use can claim to actually have read it. I'm talking about the bible. In text format it is less than 4,5 MB. Project Gutenberg has a version of King James bible and with formatting it's 5,218,805 bytes, or just a hair over 5MB.
What does that tell us? Well for instance it tells us that in a single gigabyte you can store the bible (King James from Project Gutenberg) something like 205.7 times...

Using the two links provided in the description I get a price of about $8,300 from Amazon and about $11,500 from Newegg. So a dual card setup would run somewhere between $16,600 and $23,000. Don't know what's up with the extreme price spread.
As for storage size a clean installation of Windows 10 takes up somewhere between 25 and 40 GB. It should be possible to create a smaller install but then you need to cut out a lot of things that you normally can't get rid of. But a more typical installation can easily balloon to 100 GB or more if you aren't very careful with what you install and what options you enable. So while it might be possible to install the system to a 60 GB drive it would just be waiting to blow up in your face. As a result the smallest drive that can be recommended is at least 120 GB, but even that is on the small side today.

If you are running an older version of windows then the it can be more compact, but again the installation has a tendency to grow at an alarming rate.

As for *nix it can be much smaller and could easily run a usable but not necessarily posh system on a 40 GB drive. A "normal" installation however is a bit larger, and again even a 60GB drive is on the small side if you are going to store anything locally.

What is really interesting is that PS5 and Series X are both doing this same thing. That is the "Super special SSD tech" that Sony was talking about. So I'm pretty stoked to see if it can become standard in gaming cards to have 1TB in NVME storage and whatever GDDR directly on the card so games can load massive super detailed assets and world's. Should be siiiiick

@Matt D Well it's hard to say really. The SSG was truly a beta product. It only came with a dev kit. No software supported the card, so it had to be written from scratch essentially. And the cards weren't even Polaris. So they were out of date in a lot of ways.

So maybe AMD has just been trying to find a cost effective way to use this idea in a way that makes sense? Game consoles would be a great way to do that. Idk, time will tell. I definitely don't disagree with you tho.

@Dan Larkin It seems like a good idea, but with the AMD Radeon‚Ñ¢ Pro SSG debuting in 2017 and already seeming to be dead (I don't see ANY of the tech amongst the current ultra high end offerings on amd.com) I think it's an idea that simply hasn't panned out in the real world.

Perhaps it will be revisited in future with PCIe4 driving SSD performance higher and higher. Perhaps the drop in price of GDDR6 or the massive bandwidth of PCIe4 giving excess bandwidth for access to main memory or PCIe4 SSDs has killed it stone dead.

Conceptually, it doesn't seem all that different from "TurboCache" cards of the 6x00 series. Cheap out with small amounts of real ram and rely on lots of slow cheap memory to make up a shortfall.

I like how there's ECC memory when a significant number of the GPU's functions are non-deterministic. Of course you can force determinism, but it usually destroys performance.

@Jarrod Christman Oh there's loads and loads of areas in GPUs which aren't deterministic. Even simple things like multiplying the exact same two floating points can give you different answers. For the exact spec you'd need to look at the exact GPU architecture and implementation (since this isn't standardized). If you look at something like TensorFlow the non-determinism is so strong that it can lead to significantly different models.


GPUs have a history of use in areas where determinism really isn't that important. Who cares in video games, non-technical rendering, most machine learning, etc.Of course if you're simulating bridges or rockets it likely matters much more to you.



While there certainly are many areas where the determinism is worth it, it's also just not in many. Machine learning for example doesn't really care, most of ML is already so wavey and probabilistic that GPU uncertainty doesn't add that much. Especially since cutting edge models are so expensive to train, the speed boost (and hence less hardware needed) you get from non-determinism is massive.

What non-determistic functions are you talking about? Also keep in mind Quadros are largely for GPU compute loads, where error correction is most certainly appreciated. Even things like floating point calculations, which of course have round off error buildup, but that round off is still deterministic.

When your talking professionals in computer animation and content creation we are a different breed of folks. I have had in some cases 2 and 3 instances of max open or max and a couple instances of a image editor etc or max and a game that id be working on in some capacity. So i might run max x1 instance say gimp or photo shop x 1 a game and other misc applications that all hit the gpu and video ram. Doing all of this at once would make your dual titan set up choke to death while doing it on the quadro or a amd w line card it would go is that all you got? At the same time though driver tweaks and bios tweaks and ram type ecc vs non ecc will result in a poorer game play experience. They are just not made to actually game on and the various driver and bios differences will show this. There are ways you can use non dev drivers on the dev cards and vise versa which will result in better performance in games or 3d etc work but not as good as a card made for the intended purpose.



But if your like me and do allot of on the fly development you may not want to wait for a file transfer to finish even if it is a couple seconds when you can simply send off to your game editor and then to the game in question all by save as or export. Eg unreal 4.2 world editor and max you would export to fbx right in to your projects working directory refresh the asset list pull the model in and have it game client ready and drop in to the proper sport mod style test in game if satisfied build the new client and push it as a patch.



Running unreal engine and max and a game client is a mammoth resource hit system wide from your cpu and system ram to your gpu and vram. I could easily push every thing to 80 or 90% used with all running. 5 grand for a gpu is in the field pretty affordable 1 month of a 1 to 3 year contract with a game co could pay for that card 2 or 3 times over.



even a hobbyist could pay that card off selling their models on various asset stores (unity epic or even turbo squid) pretty quick. Expensive yes compared to gaming cards but worth it with out doubt...
